  "summary": "A dense, contemplative, eco-spiritual Haggadah with powerful inner-work interpretations and a full traditional structure; its enduring ritual and ethical sequences are valuable, while numerous 2026 political passages must remain research-only or explicitly contextualized.",
  "sourceAssessment": {
    "voice": "Meditative, mystical, eco-spiritual, justice-oriented, textually learned, and often written for adults already comfortable with Jewish liturgy and contemporary activism.",
    "bestUses": [
      "Mindfulness and spiritual-depth interpretations woven into traditional ritual moments",
      "A concise ethical Exodus telling focused on oppression, cry, and responsibility",
      "Meal and blessing passages that connect bodily action, gratitude, ecology, and peace"
    ],
    "beginnerRisks": [
      "The source frequently assumes knowledge of Hebrew, rabbinic concepts, mystical vocabulary, and the traditional Seder sequence.",
      "Many passages address specific 2026 political events and can become outdated or partisan when detached from their source context.",
      "Long interpretive units can overwhelm a short or mixed-age Seder unless paired with concrete action cues and trimmed as complete movements."
    ],
    "politicalContext": "The edition openly advocates Palestinian dignity, opposes settler violence and war, and also affirms Jewish and Israeli actors working for safety and peace. Those commitments align with shared humanity, but event-specific allegations, party or government references, and contemporary conflict claims must not enter default modules without current sourcing and an explicit opt-in.",
    "creditContext": "Credit Rabbi David Seidenberg and neohasid.org, link the CC BY-SA 4.0 license, identify modifications, and preserve ShareAlike terms. The source contains many embedded readings, translations, and poems that require their own credit and rights review."
  },
